It’s [Monotype Modern](http://web.archive.org/web/20090607101825/http:/new.myfonts.com/fonts/linotype/monotype-modern/), the favored font for math and math-heavy books at the time. It’s been largely supplanted by [Computer Modern](http://web.archive.org/web/20090607101825/http:/new.myfonts.com/fonts/linotype/monotype-modern/), the TeX adaptation of the font. Note that the official Monotype digitization is not optically scaled, but the Computer Modern version is.

This [book](http://web.archive.org/web/20090607101825/http:/books.google.com/books?id=6wSVuWH1PrsC) is about calculus of variations, which I reference extensively in my [thesis](http://web.archive.org/web/20090607101825/http:/levien.com/phd/phd.html) on interpolating splines. I looked at a bunch of references and decided on [Elsgolts](http://web.archive.org/web/20090607101825/http:/www.amazon.com/Differential-Equations-Calculus-Variations-Elsgolts/dp/1410210677) instead, largely because his presentation of the Euler-Poisson equation was much more direct than most. Note also that this is a republication of the original 1952 edition, and Dover, as is typical, reproduced page images rather than retypesetting the text.

@bowfinpw: And yes, the “CONTENTS” is a different font, possibly Baskerville. Also note that the boldface is a not-quite matching font, I think it’s one of the numbered “Monotype Old Style” ones, but I’m not 100% sure.
